<section xml:id="sec-volume-of-solids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Solids</title>
    <introduction>
        <definition xml:id="def-Volume-of-prisms">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Volume}</m> is the amount of space occupied by a three-dimensional object. It tells us how much something can hold.
                </p>
                <p>
                    - If an object is hollow, its volume tells us the capacity â€“ how much 
                    liquid or air it can hold. If it is solid, volume tells us how much space it fills up.
                </p>
                <p>
                    For example,
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The volume of water in a jug.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The volume of sand in a bucket.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The volume of a classroom (helps in knowing how much air it can hold).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
    </introduction>

